<a href="http://www.acpsec.org/fr/content/98th-session-acp-council-ministers-decisions-resolutions-speeches-photos" target="_self">http://www.acpsec.org/fr/content/98th-session-acp-council-ministers-deci...</a></p><p><i>Fresh Plaza</i>, ‘Germany: Decreasing banana imports’, 28 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115577/Germany-Decreasing-banana-imports" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115577/Germany-Decreasing-banana-imports</a></p><p>FAO, ‘Fight against Black Sigatoka must continue to save small Caribbean banana farms’, 12 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/210605/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/210605/icode/</a></p><p><i>Hoy.com.do</i>, ‘Banana exports will increase to $300 billion’ 25 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115336/Dominican-Republic-Banana-exports-will-increase-to-300-billion#SlideFrame_1" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115336/Dominican-Republic-Banana-expor...</a></p><p><i>Allafrica.com</i>, ‘Agreement signed to export bananas to China’, 3 December 201</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115806/Kenya-Agreement-signed-to-export-bananas-to-China#SlideFrame_1" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/article/115806/Kenya-Agreement-signed-to-expor...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The variable experience of ACP banana exporters and the relatively strong performance of ACP banana exports overall in the last 18 months should not detract from the long-term effects of preference erosion in the banana sector and shortcomings in the functioning of some ACP–EU banana supply chains (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Agriculture/Commodities/Bananas/Unsustainable-UK-banana-pricing-policies-begin-to-spread" target="_self">Unsustainable UK banana pricing policies begin to spread</a>, 23 December 2013). One of the effects in the Caribbean has been to undermine the ability of smallholder farmers to finance measures to combat Black Sigatoka, with these “funding constraints” contributing to the spread of the disease.</p><p>The urgency of the need to get to grips with Black Sigatoka through proper funding of research, technical support and disease control programmes and the introduction of new more disease-resistant varieties suggests little justification for any underspend on allocated BAM programmes, if the necessary flexibility is applied to programming and disbursements.</p><p>Areas of potential assistance reach beyond disease control measures to embrace support for wider banana restructuring programmes, targeting the new local markets for banana products as well as speciality markets (e.g. organics and, if supply chain issues are addressed, fair-trade bananas) and the changing patterns of global demand for bananas.</p>
		</div>
		
